Perfect! I've completed comprehensive research on all external integrations. Let me provide you with a summary:

```
=== RESEARCH COMPLETE ===

Integrations Researched: 4
- Drizzle ORM: Verified ✓
- Neon PostgreSQL Serverless Driver: Verified ✓
- Apollo Server: Verified ✓
- GraphQL: Verified ✓

Unverified Claims: 0

Key Findings:

📦 VERIFIED PACKAGES:
  • drizzle-orm - TypeScript ORM with Neon-specific drivers
  • @neondatabase/serverless - Neon's official PostgreSQL driver
  • @apollo/server - GraphQL server (requires 'graphql' peer dependency)
  • graphql - Core GraphQL implementation

🔧 DRIZZLE ORM WITH NEON:
  • Two driver options:
    - drizzle-orm/neon-http (HTTP-based, lower latency for simple queries)
    - drizzle-orm/neon-serverless (WebSocket-based, better for complex operations)
  • Initialization: const db = drizzle(process.env.DATABASE_URL);
  • Query methods: select(), insert(), update(), delete()
  • Use .returning() on mutations to get inserted/updated rows

🌐 NEON SERVERLESS DRIVER:
  • Package: @neondatabase/serverless
  • Node.js v21 and earlier require 'ws' package + WebSocket config
  • Automatic connection pooling (no manual pooling needed)
  • Connection string format: postgres://user:pass@ep-*.*.aws.neon.tech/db

🚀 APOLLO SERVER INTEGRATION:
  • Pass db through context to all resolvers
  • Context pattern: context: async () => ({ db })
  • Resolver access: (_, args, { db }) => { ... }
  • Context function called per request - reuse db instance

⚠️  CRITICAL GOTCHAS:
  1. Drizzle has TWO Neon drivers - choose based on use case
  2. Node.js requires 'ws' package for neon-serverless driver
  3. WebSocket config needed: neonConfig.webSocketConstructor = ws
  4. Apollo context called every request - never create new db connections there
  5. Must install 'graphql' separately (peer dependency)
  6. Use .returning() to avoid extra SELECT queries after mutations
  7. Neon handles pooling automatically - single db instance is enough

📋 RECOMMENDED SETUP PATTERN:

// db.ts - Create once, reuse everywhere
import { drizzle } from 'drizzle-orm/neon-http';
import { neon } from '@neondatabase/serverless';

const sql = neon(process.env.DATABASE_URL!);
export const db = drizzle({ client: sql });

// server.ts - Pass through context
import { db } from './db';
const server = new ApolloServer({ typeDefs, resolvers });
await startStandaloneServer(server, {
  context: async () => ({ db })
});

// resolvers.ts - Access via context
const resolvers = {
  Query: {
    brands: async (_, __, { db }) => {
      return await db.select().from(brandsTable);
    }
  },
  Mutation: {
    createBrand: async (_, { input }, { db }) => {
      const [brand] = await db.insert(brandsTable)
        .values(input)
        .returning();
      return brand;
    }
  }
};

Recommendations:
  1. Use neon-http driver for simpler, lower-latency queries
  2. Create centralized db module that exports single Drizzle instance
  3. Pass db through Apollo context to all resolvers
  4. Use .returning() on all mutations for efficiency
  5. Implement proper error handling (throw GraphQLError on failures)
  6. Create helper functions for common query patterns (50+ resolvers!)
  7. Verify all Drizzle schema definitions exist before implementation

Next Steps for Architect Phase:
  • Inventory all 50+ resolver locations
  • Verify Drizzle schemas exist for all tables
  • Map resolvers to database tables
  • Design error handling strategy
  • Plan incremental vs all-at-once migration

research.json created successfully ✓
```

All integrations have been thoroughly researched and validated using Context7 MCP, which provided official documentation with code examples. The research file contains complete API patterns, configuration requirements, and critical gotchas that will guide the implementation phase.

